<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,743,975]" pageId="10" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName box="[151,359,743,767]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Platynota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stultana">
<emphasis box="[151,359,743,767]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="41">Platynota stultana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the omnivorous leafroller, was introduced into southern California in the late 
<number box="[1265,1325,743,767]" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" value="1800.0">1800</number>
â€™s (Powell and Opler 
<number box="[268,329,777,801]" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" value="2009.0">2009</number>
). It has subsequently expanded its range into northern California, while at the same time expanding its host range onto a variety of non-native plants (
<bibRefCitation author="Powell" box="[719,868,812,836]" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" refString="Powell, J. A. 1983. Expanding geographical and ecological range of Platynota stultana in California (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae). The Pan-Pacific Entomologist, 59, 233 - 239." type="journal article" year="1983">
Powell 
<number box="[808,868,812,836]" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" value="1983.0">1983</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). This species is considered a pest in greenhouses and vineyards, but it also attacks row crops, citrus, and occasionally avocado. Adults are present year round in southern and central California. Larvae feed primarily in shelters constructed of rolled or folded leaves. Economic damage occurs when larvae web leaves to fruit or feed directly on fruit, causing superficial damage and secondary infection by bacteria and fungi.
</paragraph>
